04207nam a22005775i 9780300144208DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20082008ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a97803001442087 a10.12987/97803001442082doi  a(DE-B1597)484824  a(OCoLC)1013948507  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT 4aDK266b.H477 2000eb 7aPOL0050002bisacsh04a321.9/2/094/090482211 aHollander, Paul, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPolitical Will and Personal Belief :bThe Decline and Fall of Soviet Communism /cPaul Hollander. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[2008] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (368 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tChapter 1. The Human Factor in the Failure of Communism -- tChapter 2. Defectors and Exiles: Disillusionment Before the Fall -- tChapter 3. Soviet Leaders: The Reformers -- tChapter 4. The Ambivalence of High-Level Functionaries -- tChapter 5. The Political Transformation of East European Leaders -- tChapter 6. Leading Specialists in “State Security” (Political Police) -- tChapter 7. Conclusions: The Unity of Theory and Practice -- tAppendix: The Interviews -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe unexpected collapse of the Soviet Union in 1991 signaled the demise of a political and economic system that was widely perceived as durable, the preeminent rival to that of the United States. Less conspicuous than the momentous political transformations were the altered beliefs, aspirations, and illusions of the individuals who had maintained and led that system. In this original interpretation the eminent sociologist Paul Hollander focuses on the human aspects of the failure of Soviet communism. He examines how members of the Soviet political elite, leaders in communist Czechoslovakia and Hungary, high-ranking officials in agencies of control and coercion, and distinguished defectors and exiles experienced the erosion of ideals that undermined the political system they had once believed in.Hollander analyzes an array of autobiographical and biographical writings, journalistic accounts, and scholarly interpretations of the unraveling of Soviet communism. The Soviet Union fell apart not merely because of severe economic shortcomings, Hollander argues, but because of the double impact of the conflict between official ideals and practical realities and an eroding sense of legitimacy in the highest echelons. In his conclusion, the author considers how Marxist theory both shaped and undermined the system.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCommunismzEurope, EasternxHistory. 0aCommunismzSoviet UnionxHistory. 0aCommunist leadershipzEurope, Eastern. 0aCommunist leadershipzSoviet Union. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Ideologies / Communism, Post-Communism & Socialism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831105379940 cprintz978030007620240uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030014420840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300144208423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300144208/original  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY